reviewText: This is a TV movie, so we don't expect fancy effects or expensive sets and that is definitely the case here. This is the story of a girl who gets stuck next to a guy at a wedding that she takes a dislike to. A somewhat hard-to-believe situation involving her moving van being stolen leads to her making a deal with him to stage a fake wedding in order to get presents to outfit the house. The seem to despise each other but be willing to work together. As the movie progresses, the guy, who happens to be in debt to a loan shark, starts to make a better impression and they inevitably start to fall for each other. The whole part of the plot that involves the plan to get presents is fairly ridiculous but it doesn't overpower the aspects of the plot that involve the relationship between the two characters. The movie will never win any awards for great writing or acting, but somehow, in the end, it kind of works and leaves you with a nice feeling in spite of a number of shortfalls. As far as TV romantic comedies go, this one is probably just a bit above average and worth checking out if you want a low-key and clean movie to watch.

reviewText: I am sorry to be the stinker in the barrel on this one but it was just way too predicatable for me.  Also, the acting was too cheeky.  I really like Melisa Joan Hart and wanted to like this movie but it just left me cold.  I think my negative review also has to do with the plot of the movie.  She is playing the part of the more 'mature' one in the relationship yet is willing to bilk all her family and friends for the sake of getting a bunch of money and stuff from a fake/arranged marriage.  I think she just came across as shallow as Joey in the movie.  If the comedy was better in the movie it might make the selfishness of the plot less glaring.  Maybe I am a bit of a traditionalist, but getting married should either be taken seriously or the movie should have better acting with a black comedy.  Keep trying Melisa, I am rooting for a better film the next time.

reviewText: This is a great little screwball comedy about a farce of a romance perpetrated to bring in a desperately needed haul of household furnishings and cash to pay off a debt to the mob! Hey, if two desperate people need "stuff," why not announce your engagement, register at department stores, and sit back waiting for the haul to arrive?What could possibly go wrong?For Milissa Joan Hart and Joey Lawrence, the sham romance turns out to be real, much to their surprise. This movie is tremendous fun, and not to be missed!

reviewText: Melissa Joan Hart and Joey Lawrence are some of my favorite performers on television, and I am a big fan of their current sitcom "Melissa & Joey" on ABC Family. The ABC family's Christmas movie, "Holiday in Handcuffs," is another hilarious movie, which caused my interest in this movie. This is about two young people named Jennifer (Melissa Joan Hart) and Vince (Joey Lawrence) who find themselves in need of cash come up with a quick plan to rise cash faking a relationship, engagement and a shotgun wedding. Hoping to get lots off gifts which they hope to use to pay off Vince's loan shark friends and Jennifer to buy the house-wares to fill her home after her moving van is stolen. It is absolutely hilarious to watch the couple trying to convince their families that they are really in love.  In this process the families come to believe that Jennifer is pregnant and the women in the family get very excited. This sudden interest of everyone else in Jennifer's and Vince's fake wedding make the young couples fall in "real" love with each other. This is an outstanding movie which I am sure you will laugh like I did as the move progresses; highly recommended.1.Melissa & Joey: Season One, Part One2.Holiday in Handcuffs3.Melissa & Joey: Season One, Part Two4.Sabrina, The Teenage Witch: The Complete Series

reviewText: After Seeing Melissa Joan Hart and Joseph Lawrence on ABC Family's Melissa & Joey, I had to see this video.  Apparently the chemistry between these 2 young actors was discovered in this film.Jennifer (Melissa) and Vince (Joseph) agree to plan a fake wedding after she loses all her possessions while moving and his bookie demands the $15k he owes. At one point Vince doesn't want to take money from his dad but does it for her. Jennifer doesn't want to go through with the fraud to her family and friends but agrees to do it for him.Jennifer decides to allow Vince to sleep on her bed, on top of the covers and they briefly kiss but a family issue demands their attention.  A couple of times Jennifer is asked if she is 'Preggo' so there really isn't any bad language or situations.Melissa and Joseph are in perfect timing throughout the film, their years as child actors has taught them much.If a happy ending is predictable, well then it is. However all that Jennifer and Vince go through while planning their wedding makes an enjoyable story.

reviewText: Haven't we been down this road already, Melissa Joan Hart? Jennifer (MJH) meets Vince (Joey Lawrence) at a wedding. They have an immediate disliking for each other. Jennifer has all of her belongings stolen, and Vince has a gambling debt due to The Monkey (Steve Schirripa). They decide to arrange a fake wedding, as "business partners," to cash in on all of the gifts. They then part ways and never see each other again. Actually, I think you can see where this one is going. My Fake Fiancé was a made-for-tv movie on ABC Family, so I guess I should have known what I was getting into. If you care to see an identical plot with a younger MJH, see Drive Me Crazy.
